  <!-- ===== About ===== -->
  <data name="About.Tagline" xml:space="preserve"><value>The control center this laptop should have shipped with.</value></data>
  <data name="About.WhyTitle" xml:space="preserve"><value>WHY THIS EXISTS</value></data>
  <data name="About.Why.P1" xml:space="preserve"><value>I bought a top-spec Avell laptop in 2018. The fan curve, the performance modes, the keyboard lighting, all of it lived inside Avell's Gaming Center app. Then Avell dropped it. No updates, no fixes, just abandonware that I still had to keep installed to control my own machine.</value></data>
  <data name="About.Why.P2" xml:space="preserve"><value>So I reverse engineered it and wrote my own. The name says how I feel about being left with dead software on hardware I paid a lot for.</value></data>
  <data name="About.Why.P3" xml:space="preserve"><value>It talks to the same hardware the old app did: the same EC registers, the same power plans. The difference is it's fast, it's mine, and it tells the truth. If a write to the hardware doesn't stick, it says so instead of pretending it worked.</value></data>
  <data name="About.Why.P4" xml:space="preserve"><value>The RGB tab is unfinished, and there's a reason. Around two years in, I opened the laptop to clean it and found the keyboard ribbon connector cracked and held together with a piece of tape. From the factory. The keyboard was already dying and there was no real way to fix it. Avell couldn't help, the warranty was gone, and it didn't matter that the fault was theirs to begin with. So the keyboard on this machine no longer works, which means the RGB lighting cannot be tested. The code is here, the hardware is not.</value></data>
  <data name="About.HowTitle" xml:space="preserve"><value>HOW IT WORKS</value></data>
  <data name="About.How.P1" xml:space="preserve"><value>Fan and power settings live in the Embedded Controller's memory. The app reads and writes it through a WMI ACPI method (AcpiTest_MULong), the same path the old app used. Every write is checked against an allowlist, read back to confirm it landed, and rolled back if it didn't. All of it goes to an audit log. Performance modes also switch the machine's Windows power plan. Sensor readings refresh about once a second, and if you change something outside the app it shows up here within a couple of seconds.</value></data>
  <data name="About.How.Tech" xml:space="preserve"><value>WPF, .NET 10. Reverse engineered from the OEM app plus a lot of live poking at the hardware.</value></data>
